      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Apologies for the goblin analogy! Let's dive into the physics of air pressure and speed. In the context of Bernoulli's principle, when air moves faster, it has less time to exert force on the surrounding air molecules, which results in a reduction of pressure. Picture a crowd of people rushing to get through a narrow doorway. The faster they move, the less time they have to push against the door, making it easier to pass through. Similarly, when air moves quickly over the top of the wing, it exerts less pressure on the air below, creating the pressure difference that results in lift. The wing's shape, or airfoil, is designed to maximize this effect, with a longer upper surface to increase the speed of the air above and a shorter lower surface to slow it down, enhancing the pressure difference and thus the lift.",
